This project develops a predictive analytics system for EduPro, an online learning platform, to support data-driven decision-making in course planning, pricing, and resource allocation. Traditional planning approaches at EduPro rely heavily on historical reporting and intuition, limiting the ability to proactively forecast course demand and optimize revenue. This work introduces machine learning–based models to estimate enrollment demand and course-level revenue.

The analysis integrates multi-source platform data, including course attributes, instructor information, and transaction records. Transaction-level data were aggregated to construct a course-level dataset containing key performance indicators such as enrollment count and total revenue. A structured data engineering pipeline was implemented to clean, merge, and transform the data, along with feature engineering techniques including price bands, duration buckets, rating tiers, and encoded course levels.

A critical focus of this project was ensuring leakage-free modeling, where features derived from target variables (e.g., aggregated revenue or enrollment proxies) were explicitly removed to maintain realistic predictive performance. This resulted in models that reflect true generalization capability rather than inflated accuracy.

Exploratory analysis revealed strong price sensitivity in revenue generation and noticeable variation across course categories. While revenue exhibited predictable patterns driven largely by pricing, enrollment demand showed weak predictability due to the absence of behavioral and temporal features such as user preferences and market trends.

Multiple machine learning models were evaluated, including Linear Regression, Ridge, Lasso, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting. Ridge Regression emerged as the best-performing model for revenue prediction, achieving high accuracy and stability on a limited dataset. In contrast, enrollment prediction models demonstrated low explanatory power, highlighting the complexity of demand forecasting and the limitations of available features.

To operationalize the results, an interactive Streamlit dashboard was developed. The application enables users to input course parameters such as price, duration, level, and instructor attributes, and receive real-time predictions for enrollment and revenue. The dashboard also includes advanced analytical features such as revenue–price simulation, optimal pricing recommendation, feature importance visualization, and category-level performance comparison. Business rules were incorporated to enforce logical constraints, such as zero revenue for free courses.

The project is structured into modular components, including data preparation, feature engineering, modeling, and deployment scripts, ensuring reproducibility and scalability. The final system serves as a decision-support tool that not only predicts outcomes but also provides actionable insights for pricing optimization and course portfolio strategy.

Overall, this work demonstrates how predictive modeling, when combined with domain constraints and interactive visualization, can transform EduPro’s planning process from reactive analysis to proactive, data-driven decision-making, while also highlighting the challenges of accurately modeling human-driven demand.
